@NODE Starting "Starting PSX Control"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  PSX@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}Control v1.0  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·       @{U}STARTING IT@{UU}        · @{UB}

   You can start PSX-Control without modifying any settings in the icon tooltypes,
   but it is advised that you at least have a look at them and adapt them where
   necessary.

   PSX-Control can be started from the CLI and from the Workbench.

   @{B}@{U}CLI usage@{ub}@{uu}

   PSX-Control accepts the following parameters:

     @{b}D=DEVICE@{ub}     -   The devicename where the Net Yaroze cable is connected to
                      (eg. serial.device / duart.device / gvpserial.device / ...)
                      Default: @{i}serial.device@{ui}

     @{b}U=UNIT@{ub}       -   The device unit where the Net Yaroze cable is connected to
                      NOTE: Only units from 0 - 9 are valid
                      Default: @{i}0@{ui}

     @{b}B=BAUD@{ub}       -   The baudrate the Net Yaroze BootCD is currently operating
                      at. The baudrate can be found at the main screen of the
                      Yaroze Terminal (as "Terminal baudrate <baudrate>").
                      Default: @{i}9600@{ui}

     @{b}PSXDEBUG@{ub}     -   Open a special debug window when you execute a PSX executable.
                      Default: @{i}No debug information@{ui}

     @{b}SETRATE@{ub}      -   Set the PSX Terminal's baudrate to the baudrate you specified
                      after the "BAUD" tooltype upon startup. This takes a
                      few seconds at startup and is only usefull when your
                      memorycards are always full ;)
                      Default: @{i}No@{ui}

     @{b}LOGFILE@{ub}      -   If you want to keep a log of all actions, then you can
                      specify a logfile here. Only recommended for PSX-Control
                      debugging purposes. Note: This logfile grows fast!
                      Default: @{i}No logging@{ui}

   @{u}Some examples:@{uu}

    PSXControl DEVICE=serial.device UNIT=0 BAUD=9600 PSXDEBUG SETRATE

    PSXControl D=serial.device U=0 B=9600 PSXDEBUG SETRATE


   @{B}@{U}Tooltypes@{ub}@{uu}

   PSX-Control is a commodity. The following default commodity-tooltypes are
   recognized and used:

     @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}     -  Set this to "YES" if you want PSX-Control to open it's
                     window at startup. Set it to "NO" otherwise.
                     Default: @{i}YES@{ui}
     @{b}CX_PRI@{ub}       -  Commodity priority. Should only be set to 0.
                     Default: @{i}0@{ui}
     @{b}CX_HOTKEY@{ub}    -  If PSX-Control is hidden, you can wake it up again with
                     the keycombination you enter here.
                     Default: @{i}alt f5@{ui}

   Following are the PSX-Control related tooltypes:

     @{b}DEVICE@{ub}       -   The devicename where the Net Yaroze cable is connected to
                      (eg. serial.device / duart.device / gvpserial.device / ...)
                      Default: @{i}serial.device@{ui}

     @{b}UNIT@{ub}         -   The device unit where the Net Yaroze cable is connected to
                      NOTE: Only units from 0 - 9 are valid
                      Default: @{i}0@{ui}

     @{b}BAUD@{ub}         -   The baudrate the Net Yaroze BootCD is currently operating
                      at. The baudrate can be found at the main screen of the
                      Yaroze Terminal (as "Terminal baudrate <baudrate>").
                      Default: @{i}9600@{ui}

     @{b}PSXDEBUG@{ub}     -   Open a special debug window when you execute a PSX executable.
                      Default: @{i}No debug information@{ui}

     @{b}SETRATE@{ub}      -   Set the PSX Terminal's baudrate to the baudrate you specified
                      after the "BAUD" tooltype upon startup. This takes a
                      few seconds at startup and is only usefull when your
                      memorycards are always full ;)
                      Default: @{i}No@{ui}

     @{b}LOGFILE@{ub}      -   If you want to keep a log of all actions, then you can
                      specify a logfile here. Only recommended for PSX-Control
                      debugging purposes. Note: This logfile grows fast!
                      Default: @{i}No logging@{ui}

   When you save the preferences in PSX Control, then the tooltypes in the icon
   will be changed to your new preferences.

@ENDNODE

