@NODE Scripting "Executing scripts with PSX Control"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  PSX@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}Control v1.0  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·    @{U}EXECUTING SCRIPTS@{UU}        · @{UB}

   Scripts are small textfiles that contain commands for PSX-Control.
   Some of these commands include transferring of files, starting programs,
   displaying texts to the user, ...

   PSX-Control recognizes scripts that were made for SIOCONS, CAETLA and
   EZ-O-RAY (three different development systems for the Yaroze and the
   regular Playstation).

   Following is a list of all the recognized commands and their meaning:

   @{b}@{u}SIOCONS commands:@{ub}@{uu}

    @{b}quit      @{ub}  - Stop the execution of the script
                  Command format: @{i}quit@{ui}
    @{b}load      @{ub}  - Load an executable file to the Yaroze
                  Command format: @{i}load <filename>@{ui}
    @{b}dload     @{ub}  - Load a data file to the Yaroze
                  Command format: @{i}dload <address> <filename>@{ui}
    @{b}auto-again@{ub}  - Restart the script
                  Command format: @{i}auto-again@{ui}
    @{b}sleep     @{ub}  - Wait a number of seconds
                  Command format: @{i}sleep <number>@{ui}
    @{b}pause     @{ub}  - Display a text and wait 1 second
                  Command format: @{i}pause <text>@{ui}
    @{b}echo      @{ub}  - Display a text to the user
                  Command format: @{i}echo <text>@{ui}
    @{b}beep      @{ub}  - Make a sound.
                  Command format: @{i}beep@{ui}

   @{b}@{u}CAETLA commands:@{ub}@{uu}

    None implemented at the moment

   @{b}@{u}EZ-O-RAY commands:@{ub}@{uu}

    @{b}ezoray load@{ub} - Load a data file to the Yaroze
                  Command format: @{i}ezoray load <address> <filename>@{ui}
    @{b}ezoray run @{ub} - Load and execute an executable file.
                  Command format: @{i}ezoray run <filename>@{ui}

   On the Amiga, you are allowed to mix all these commands (since PSX-Control
   will recognize them all). Remember that PC and Macintosh users only use
   @{b}one@{ub} type of development system and that their systems will not
   recognize files that have mixed commands.

@ENDNODE

